        <tr> 
          <td><textarea name="textarea" cols="40" rows="30" readonly>Image 514

In this 1480 stained glass panel (East Harling, Norfolk: East window, B3), Christ is embraced in a bear-hug by a rather hairy and ugly Judas, who wears a purple robe. The panel is crowded with helmeted soldiers. One to the right holds a lantern. Another holds aloft (centre top) a brazier on a pole, with red flames rising from it. Soldiers behind hold up halberds and spears. The helmet of the leftmost soldier has a bird's claw, perhaps a crest. To the right, St Peter cuts off Malchus's ear with his sword. Only Judas and Malchus have flesh-coloured faces (that of Judas is darkened). The inscription (top) reads:'Capt' es(t) ihesus'.

Woodforde 1950, p.48
(see also Image 511)</textarea></td>
